{"type":"session_message","session_id":"ses_288963eb6ffeaPeCtB5dMDgj3X","role":"assistant","message_id":"msg_d7769d5c4001c5f7q7zqR5z5T4","parts":[{"id":"prt_d7769e07f001uQ324gW2P08MTw","messageID":"msg_d7769d5c4001c5f7q7zqR5z5T4","sessionID":"ses_288963eb6ffeaPeCtB5dMDgj3X","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_73ce24f51bcf49c2874e9e9c","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/workspace/INSTALL.rst"},"output":"<path>/workspace/INSTALL.rst</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: .. _installation:\n2: \n3: Installation\n4: ============\n5: \n6: The Kernel Tuner requires several packages to be installed. First of all, you need a\n7: working Python version, several Python packages, and optionally CUDA and/or OpenCL\n8: installations. All of this is explained in detail in this guide.\n9: \n10: For comprehensive step-by-step instructions on setting up a development environment, see :ref:`Development Environment <dev-environment>`.\n11: \n12: Python\n13: ------\n14: \n15: You need a Python installation. We recommend using Python 3 and installing it with `Miniconda <https://conda.io/miniconda.html>`__.\n16: Linux users could type the following to download and install Python 3 using Miniconda:\n17: \n18: .. code-block:: bash\n19: \n20:     wget https://repo.continuum.io/miniconda/Miniconda3-latest-Linux-x86_64.sh\n21:     bash Miniconda3-latest-Linux-x86_64.sh\n22: \n23: You are of course also free to use your own Python installation, and the Kernel Tuner is developed to be fully compatible with Python 3.10 and newer.\n24: \n25: Installing Python Packages\n26: --------------------------\n27: \n28: Note that when you are using a native Python installation, the `pip` command used \n29: to install\n30: Kernel Tuner and its dependencies requires `sudo` rights for system wide installation. \n31: \n32: Sudo rights are typically not required when using Miniconda or virtual environments.\n33: You could also use e.g. the `--user` or `--prefix` option of `pip` to install into\n34: your home directory,\n35: this requires that your home directory is on your `$PYTHONPATH` environment variable\n36: (see for further details the pip documentation).\n37: \n38: The following command will install Kernel Tuner together with the required dependencies:\n39: \n40: .. code-block:: bash\n41: \n42:     pip install kernel_tuner\n43: \n44: There are also optional dependencies, explained below.\n45: \n46: \n47: .. _installing cuda:\n48: \n49: CUDA and PyCUDA\n50: ---------------\n51: \n52: Installing CUDA and PyCUDA is optional, because you may want to only use Kernel\n53: Tuner for tuning OpenCL or C kernels.\n54: \n55: If you want to use the Kernel Tuner to tune\n56: CUDA kernels you will first need to install the CUDA toolkit\n57: (https://developer.nvidia.com/cuda-toolkit). A recent version of the\n58: CUDA toolkit (and the PyCUDA Python bindings for CUDA) are\n59: recommended (older version may work, but may not support all features of\n60: Kernel Tuner).\n61: \n62: It's very important that you install the CUDA toolkit before trying to install PyCuda.\n63: \n64: You can install PyCuda manually using:\n65: \n66: .. code-block:: bash\n67: \n68:     pip install pycuda\n69: \n70: Or you could install Kernel Tuner and PyCUDA together if you haven't done so already:\n71: \n72: .. code-block:: bash\n73: \n74:     pip install kernel_tuner[cuda]\n75: \n76: If you run into trouble with installing PyCuda, make sure you have CUDA installed first.\n77: Also make sure that the Python package Numpy is already installed, e.g. using `pip install numpy`.\n78: \n79: If you retry the ``pip install pycuda`` command, you may need to use the\n80: ``--no-cache-dir`` option to ensure the pycuda installation really starts over and not continues\n81: from an installation that is failing.\n82: \n83: If this fails, I recommend to see the PyCuda installation guide (https://wiki.tiker.net/PyCuda/Installation)\n84: \n85: \n86: Other CUDA Backends\n87: -------------------\n88: \n89: Kernel Tuner can also be used with CuPy (https://cupy.dev/) or Nvidia's CUDA Python bindings (https://nvidia.github.io/cuda-python/). Please see the installation instructions of those projects for how the required Python packages.\n90: \n91: Please refer to the documentation on `backends <https://kerneltuner.github.io/kernel_tuner/stable/backends.html>`__ on how to use and select these backends.\n92: \n93: \n94: \n95: OpenCL and PyOpenCL\n96: -------------------\n97: \n98: Before we can install PyOpenCL you'll need an OpenCL compiler. There are several\n99: OpenCL compilers available depending on the OpenCL platform you want to your\n100: code to run on.\n101: \n102: * `AMD APP SDK <https://rocmdocs.amd.com/en/latest/Programming_Guides/Opencl-programming-guide.html>`__\n103: * `Intel OpenCL <https://software.intel.com/en-us/iocl_rt_ref>`__\n104: * `CUDA Toolkit <https://developer.nvidia.com/cuda-toolkit>`__\n105: * `Apple OpenCL <https://developer.apple.com/opencl/>`__\n106: * `Beignet <https://www.freedesktop.org/wiki/Software/Beignet/>`__\n107: \n108: You can also look at this `OpenCL Installation Guide <https://wiki.tiker.net/OpenCLHowTo>`__ for PyOpenCL.\n109: \n110: As with the CUDA toolkit, recent versions of one or more of the above OpenCL SDK's and\n111: PyOpenCL are recommended to support all features of the Kernel Tuner.\n112: \n113: After you've installed your OpenCL compiler of choice you can install PyOpenCL using:\n114: \n115: .. code-block:: bash\n116: \n117:     pip install pyopencl\n118: \n119: Or you could install Kernel Tuner and PyOpenCL together if you haven't done so already:\n120: \n121: .. code-block:: bash\n122: \n123:     pip install kernel_tuner[opencl]\n124: \n125: If this fails, please see the PyOpenCL installation guide (https://wiki.tiker.net/PyOpenCL/Installation)\n126: \n127: HIP and HIP Python\n128: ------------------\n129: \n130: Before we can install HIP Python, you'll need to have the HIP runtime and compiler installed on your system.\n131: The HIP compiler is included as part of the ROCm software stack. Here is AMD's installation guide:\n132: \n133: * `ROCm Documentation: HIP Installation Guide <https://docs.amd.com/bundle/HIP-Installation-Guide-v5.3/page/Introduction_to_HIP_Installation_Guide.html>`__\n134: \n135: After you've installed HIP, you will need to install HIP Python. Run the following command in your terminal to install:\n136: \n137: First identify the first three digits of the version number of your ROCm™ installation.\n138: Then install the HIP Python package(s) as follows:\n139: \n140: .. code-block:: shell\n141: \n142:     python3 -m pip install -i https://test.pypi.org/simple hip-python~=$rocm_version\n143:     # if you want to install the CUDA Python interoperability package too, run:\n144:     python3 -m pip install -i https://test.pypi.org/simple hip-python-as-cuda~=$rocm_version\n145: \n146: For other installation options check `hip-python on GitHub <https://github.com/ROCm/hip-python>`_\n147: \n148: Installing the git version\n149: --------------------------\n150: \n151: You can also install from the git repository. This way you also get the examples.\n152: Please note that this will install all required dependencies in the current environment.\n153: For step-by-step instructions on setting up a development environment, see :ref:`Development Environment <dev-environment>`.\n154: \n155: .. code-block:: bash\n156: \n157:     git clone https://github.com/benvanwerkhoven/kernel_tuner.git\n158:     cd kernel_tuner\n159:     curl -sSL https://install.python-poetry.org | python3 -\n160:     poetry install\n161: \n162: You can install Kernel Tuner with several optional dependencies.\n163: In this we differentiate between development and runtime dependencies.\n164: The development dependencies are ``test`` and ``docs``, and can be installed by appending e.g. ``--with test,docs``.\n165: The runtime dependencies are:\n166: \n167: - `cuda`: install pycuda along with kernel_tuner\n168: - `opencl`: install pycuda along with kernel_tuner\n169: - `hip`: install HIP Python along with kernel_tuner\n170: - `tutorial`: install packages required to run the guides\n171: \n172: These can be installed by appending e.g. ``-E cuda -E opencl -E hip``.\n173: If you want to go all-out, use ``--all-extras``.\n174: \n175: For example, use:\n176: .. code-block:: bash\n177: \n178:     poetry install --with test,docs -E cuda -E opencl\n179: \n180: To install Kernel Tuner along with all the packages required for development.\n181: \n182: \n183: Dependencies for the guides\n184: ---------------------------\n185: \n186: Some addition Python packages are required to run the Jupyter notebook guides.\n187: These packages are commonly used and chances are that you already have these installed.\n188: \n189: However, to install Kernel Tuner along with the dependencies to run the guides,\n190: you could use:\n191: \n192: .. code-block:: bash\n193: \n194:     pip install kernel_tuner[tutorial,cuda]\n195: \n196: Or if you have already installed Kernel Tuner and PyCUDA, just use:\n197: \n198: .. code-block:: bash\n199: \n200:     pip install jupyter matplotlib pandas\n\n(End of file - total 200 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":".. _installation:\n\nInstallation\n============\n\nThe Kernel Tuner requires several packages to be installed. First of all, you need a\nworking Python version, several Python packages, and optionally CUDA and/or OpenCL\ninstallations. All of this is explained in detail in this guide.\n\nFor comprehensive step-by-step instructions on setting up a development environment, see :ref:`Development Environment <dev-environment>`.\n\nPython\n------\n\nYou need a Python installation. We recommend using Python 3 and installing it with `Miniconda <https://conda.io/miniconda.html>`__.\nLinux users could type the following to download and install Python 3 using Miniconda:\n\n.. code-block:: bash\n\n    wget https://repo.continuum.io/miniconda/Miniconda3-latest-Linux-x86_64.sh","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"INSTALL.rst","time":{"start":1775824920996,"end":1775824920999}}}]}
